properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Lake effect snow squalls tonight. Lake effect snow squalls are expected to become organized late this afternoon or early this evening and continue into Saturday morning. Under the heaviest snow squalls, visibilities will be significantly reduced and snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm will be possible. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, blowing snow, and strong northerly winds expected Saturday and Saturday night. Possible snowfall amounts: 15 to 30 cm. Maximum wind gusts: northerly 70 or 80 km/h. Locations: Hopedale to Postville - Makkovik. Time span: Saturday and Saturday night. Remarks: Snow will develop in the Hopedale area tonight and spread slowly southward to Postville - Makkovik by Saturday morning. Strong northerly winds and blowing snow can be expected in the Hopedale area on Saturday but these winds won't reach the Postville - Makkovik area until Saturday evening. Conditions will improve on Sunday. There is still some uncertainty as to how fast the system causing these conditions will track southward along the Labrador coast which will impact the snowfall duration and thus the snowfall amounts. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Winter storm watches are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Roseau River From Gardenton To Dominion City
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Roseau River from Gardenton to Dominion City due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls are expected to develop. Under snow squall bands visibility can be reduced due to heavy snow and blowing snow, and snow can quickly accumulate. Total snowfall: locally 5 to possibly 15 cm in the most intense squalls. Maximum wind gusts: 50-60 km/h. Locations: West coast of Cape Breton and over the Highlands. Timespan: This afternoon into this evening, and Saturday afternoon into the evening. Remarks: Areas along the west coast and over the Highlands are at highest threat, with the intensity likely to be highest today. Early on Saturday, the winds and snow will diminish but will again increase Saturday afternoon into the evening. Total snowfall amounts may reach 20 cm. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Elevated pollution levels are expected or occurring. The Ministry of Environment and Climate Change Strategy in collaboration with Northern Health has issued an Air Quality Advisory for Vanderhoof because of high concentrations of fine particulate matter. This advisory is in effect until further notice. Persons with chronic underlying medical conditions should postpone strenuous exercise until the advisory is lifted. If you are experiencing symptoms such as continuing eye or throat irritation, chest discomfort, shortness of breath, cough or wheezing, follow the advice of your health care provider. Staying indoors and in air conditioned spaces helps to reduce fine particulate exposure. Exposure is particularly a concern for pregnant women, infants, the elderly and those who have diabetes, and lung or heart disease. ### For more information on current air quality, visit www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/environment/air-land-water/air. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2019-12-07T03:37:49-00:00

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Persistent snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Possible snowfall amounts: locally 15 cm or more. Location: Hawkes Bay to Trout River. Time span: tonight and Saturday. Remarks: Onshore flurries will persist today through Saturday. The highest snowfall accumulations today will be over higher elevations with much lower amounts along the coast. Conditions will become more favourable for snow squall development tonight through Saturday with potential for significant accumulations and poor visibilities over any areas under the snow squalls. Additionally, strong westerly winds gusting to 50 or 60 km/h tonight and Saturday will cause blowing snow over exposed areas, especially during the snow squalls. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visibility in fog is expected or occurring. Dense fog has been reported in the Kindersley area overnight extending into parts of southeastern Alberta. The fog will likely remain for most of the morning before slowly dissipating. Fog patches are also present in other parts of southern Saskatchewan, but are not as extensive. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
